title: Super Smash Bros. Ultimate Tournament benefiting Peaches and Mamabean
details: IMPORTANT: If you plan on playing in the tournament, please enter using this Google Form no later than 24 hours prior to the start time: https://forms.gle/RE8aVHb94yUWy4Wd6We will be hosting a 1v1, double-elimination Super Smash Bros. Ultimate tournament at The Bolt in Edens on West Campus! All funds raised will go directly to the Peaches and Mamabean (the cats) health fund which covers food, vet bills, vaccinations, flea medication, and more. We are coordinating with the primary student caretakers of the cats to make this possible. All skill levels are welcome! You'll be winning just by pitching in to take care of Peaches and Mamabean!You are encouraged to donate $6 upon entry, as this will be the sole means of fundraising for the afternoon. That amount is flexible, and you may contribute more or less than that amount as you are able. Hope to see you there!All entrants are expected to be present at 3:00PM to begin matches. If an entrant is not present for their match, it will be counted as a loss against them. If you have questions about scheduling or other aspects of the event, please email Harry Ross at hgr8@duke.edu.A meal will not be provided, so attendees are encouraged to eat beforehand.
location: The Bolt, Edens Quad, West Campus

title: English Conversation Club
details: Each Monday, International House provides a casual, small-group setting where all members of the Duke community--students, scholars, spouses, and staff--can practice conversational English.Topics include American culture, social systems, and issues related to daily life. Come and you will have chances to share your experience in the U.S. with others while practicing conversational English with the help of Duke staff volunteers. Through discussions in small groups, you will also learn about other cultures from various countries.In 2020 Fall semester, the English Conversation Club runs every Monday from 7:30 to 8:30pm (Eastern Time) virtually on Zoom. You must reigster through https://bit.ly/ECC-2020-Fall to attend the club. The Zoom link will be available after registration.Please email Ling.jin@duke.edu for more information.

title: Ex Machina Virtual Screening!
details: Join us for a screening of Ex Machina (2014) at 7pm and 10pm on Saturday! Programmer Caleb Smith meets Ava, a sentient AI in a human body, who is the invention of CEO Nathan Bateman. As the days pass, Ava seems more and more human, and Caleb questions if he may even be a robot himself. A thrilling sci-fi psychological thriller, Ex Machina examines the ethics behind autonomy and artificial intelligence.

title: City of God Virtual Screening!
details: Join us for a virtual screening of City of God (2002) at 9pm on Thursday, 10/8! (Portuguese title: Cidade de Deus.) title: Yosemite Facelift 2020: Act Local
details: From September 22nd through September 27th, the Yosemite Climbing Association will host thewith co-presenting sponsor, The North Face, and co-host, Subaru of America. Due to COVID-19, the organization created a virtual event for 2020, which allows anyone to act locally from a home base.1.) REVIEW THE TOOLKIT -to review full guidelines, including the videos on archaeology guidance and. And of course check with local public health and permit guidelines in advance of any plans.2.) TAKE THE PLEDGE - encourage people in your circle to!3.) TAKE A PHOTO - take a picture of yourself picking up trash in a local outdoor space, anytime between 9/22 - 9/27.4.) title: GPSG Community Pantry Services
details: The GPSG Community Pantry provides food, clothing, household and personal hygiene items to Graduate and Professional students at Duke University. The pantry offers a weekly grocery bag program with contactless pickup and delivery options available. Volunteers come to the GPSG House on Wednesdays after 4PM (grocery store order pickup/drop off), Thursdays 3-7PM (bag packing), and Saturdays 12-2PM (bag pickup/delivery). Pantry patrons come to the GPSG House on Saturday 12-2PM to pick up their bags or in-person shop. The University's COVID-19 guidelines are enforced (e.g., no more than one person/family in the pantry shopping room at a time; social distancing; hand/surface sanitizing). Periodically throughout the week, members of the pantry's Executive Board Team will access the house as necessary to prepare for our services.

title: End of the semester get together MIDP
details: The event is to take place during the day in the campus space. Only Duke students will be allowed.It is inspired in Amazing Race where people are put in groups and have complete challenges and compete in who accomplishes the challenges first or better.Groups will be minimum of 4 maximum of 6 people.In the end, we will have prizes for the winning group and simple prizes for all the participants.Split into groups - send each group to one Base to fulfill the challengeBase 1:"Telephone Game" with an image:There is an image/painting or photography at one end. One person has to explain details in the picture to another member of the team ( they will be talking as a normal conversation, 6 feet and masked), who runs to a third member (located in another end) who is supposed to draw the image - This can be done over several rounds: the person seeing the picture does not have to explain everything at once. But the second and third person cannot see the image at any point.If it's a group of 6 we split it into two mini-groups, but if it's 5 there are more steps in the process.Base 2:Hula hoop challengeEach person in the group has to complete 10 hula hoops in a limited timeBase 3:Guess who is the character?Have a list of several famous/ known personalities ( members of the faculty, students, famous people) in small pieces of paperEach person grabs one piece of paper from the bag and glues it into her/his forehead. (Without seeing what is written )In a circle, each person has the chance to make YES or NO questions to discover who is the character, and the other member of the group (who are seeing what is written in the paper) answer the question.Base 4Mimics challenge

title: Persian New Year (Nowruz) Celebration
details: Nowruz is the┬áIranian New Year, also known as the┬áPersian New Year, which is celebratedworldwide by various ethnolinguistic groups usually around March 21. It marks the first day of the first month (Farvardin) of the┬áIranian calendars.┬áThe moment the┬áSun┬ácrosses the┬ácelestial equator┬áand equalizes night and day is calculated exactlyevery year, and families gather together to observe the rituals.We are going to have seven performers who would perform on average15 minutes each.

title: The Mauritanian Exclusive Virtual Screening with STXFilms!
details: IMPORTANT: 75 RSVP LIMIT. Join us for a complimentary exclusive screening by STXFilms of the recently released film, The Mauritanian (2021)! Sign up at this link to secure your virtual seat today: http://stxtickets.com/OaSFq88475. Directed by Kevin Macdonald and based on the NY Times best-selling memoir "Guantánamo Diary" by Mohamedou Ould Slahi, this is the inspiring true story of Slahi's fight for freedom after being detained and imprisoned without charge by the U.S. Government for years. Alone and afraid, Slahi (Tahar Rahim) finds allies in defense attorney Nancy Hollander (Jodie Foster) and her associate Teri Duncan (Shailene Woodley) who battle the U.S. government in a fight for justice that tests their commitment to the law and their client at every turn. Their controversial advocacy, along with evidence uncovered by a formidable military prosecutor, Lt. Colonel Stuart Couch (Benedict Cumberbatch), uncovers shocking truths and ultimately proves that the human spirit cannot be locked up. Rated R.

title: GPSG Community Pantry Services
details: The GPSG Community Pantry provides food, clothing, household and personal hygiene items to Graduate and Professional students at Duke University. The pantry offers a weekly grocery bag program with contactless pickup and delivery options available. Volunteers come to the GPSG House on Wednesdays after 4PM (grocery store order pickup/drop off), Thursdays 3-7PM (bag packing), and Saturdays 12-2PM (bag pickup/delivery). Pantry patrons come to the GPSG House on Saturday 12-2PM to pick up their bags or in-person shop. The University's COVID-19 guidelines are enforced (e.g., no more than one person/family in the pantry shopping room at a time; social distancing; hand/surface sanitizing). Periodically throughout the week, members of the pantry's Executive Board Team will access the house as necessary to prepare for our services.

title: OutSouth Film Festival Watch Party
details: DukeOUT is hosting a virtual watch party to stream the film Breaking Fast from the OutSouth Film Festival.Cultures clash and passion blooms in this lively and insightful romantic comedy. Mo (Haaz Sleiman) is a gay Muslim living in West Hollywood — he's a dedicated doctor who prioritizes his faith. When his long-term relationship takes an unexpected turn, leaving him suddenly single, he discovers that finding someone who enjoys quiet evenings of cooking and conversation is challenging in a sea of guys who are focused on partying and hook-ups. But when Mo meets Kal, sparks fly, and the cute couple moves carefully into a romance that is sweet and complicated. True-to-life dialogue and richly complex and relatable characters breathe naturalistic energy into writer-director Mike Mosallam's gorgeously shot feature debut, which he expanded from his 2015 short of the same name. Funny and thoughtful, Breaking Fast — which also stars Veronica Cartwright and Patrick Sabongui — tackles deep issues of faith, friendship and sexuality with upbeat energy and a big heart.

title: Paris is Burning - Movie Screening at the Griffith Theater!
details: Join us this weekend for Paris is Burning (1990), an exploration of drag queens living in New York City and their "house" culture, which provides a sense of community and support for the flamboyant and often socially shunned performers. Groups from each house compete in elaborate balls that take cues from the world of fashion. Also touching on issues of racism and poverty, the film features interviews with a number of renowned drag queens, including Willi Ninja, Pepper LaBeija and Dorian Corey.No registration required - we take walk-ins! Please show up 15 minutes before the film starts.

title: Paprika (2006) - Movie Screening at the Griffith Theater!
details: See the film that inspired Inception, a masterwork of dreams, the unconscious, and the mind-bending. From legendary director Satoshi Kon, join us for Paprika (2006), a dazzlingly beautiful classic.No registration required - we take walk-ins! Please show up 15 minutes before the film starts.Dr. Atsuko Chiba works as a scientist by day and, under the code name "Paprika," is a dream detective at night. Atsuko and her colleagues are working on a device called the DC Mini, which is intended to help psychiatric patients, but in the wrong hands it could destroy people's minds. When a prototype is stolen, Atsuko/Paprika springs into action to recover it before damage is done.

title: les nuits de l'├óme (the nights of the soul) - Film Collection Night
details: Cinema can fill empty spaces of your life and your loneliness.-Pedro AlmodovarIt is easy to lose yourself in the fantastical world of movies, with their giant explosions, quick action sequences, and exaggerated stakes. However, there are movies out there in which you find a part of yourself. The films that we are going to show this weekend belong to this category. The characters in these films are not particularly special. They are not the chosen ones. They do not possess superpowers. They are the ordinary people who pass by you in the street and stand behind you in the checkout line. They are you! And the stakes are not the fate of the universe or humanity. The stakes are the consequences of each choice made and each course of action taken. These films do not preach. They do not take pity. They do not attempt to stir an emotion in you or work too hard to move you. They just tell stories. The stories that bestow significance to our universal humanity.No registration required - we take walk-ins! Please show up 10 minutes before the films start.

title: GPSG Community Pantry Services
details: Open to patrons on Thursdays 5pm-7pm and Saturdays 12-2PM. The GPSG Community Pantry provides food, clothing, household and personal hygiene items to Graduate and Professional students at Duke University. The pantry offers a weekly grocery bag program and prepared meal program with contactless pickup. Volunteers come to the GPSG House on Wednesdays after 4PM (grocery store order pickup/drop off), Thursdays 3-7PM (bag packing), and Saturdays 12-2PM (bag distribution). The University's COVID-19 guidelines are enforced (e.g., no more than one person/family in the pantry shopping room at a time; social distancing; hand/surface sanitizing). Periodically throughout the week, members of the pantry's Executive Board Team will access the house as necessary to prepare for our services.

title: GPSG's Deluxe Bourbon Distillery Tour and Tasting Experience
details: Tour the Triangle's only farm distillery! Explore how Mystic handmakes small batch bourbon from the ground up. See the production process first-hand from the grain fields to the bottling line, and taste the grains, aging spirits, and finished products. Our intimate deluxe tours provide an opportunity to understand details of the distilling and aging process. A cocktail will be included for each participant and tastings of ALL of their spirits including limited release bourbons and products not yet released to the public. Graduate students are welcome to bring some snacks and enjoy a picnic on Mystic's covered porch before or after the tour.

title: A Separation - Movie Screening at the Griffith Theater with the Persian Students Association!
details: In a world where there is no right or wrong, in which there is always the chance that we have made or might make the incorrect choice, in which we have to live with these realizations, how should we decide on the choices we make? This question is intelligently addressed and masterfully depicted in the morally complicated film made by two-time Oscar winner Asghar Farhadi.A Separation is the story of a couple who decide to divorce each other because each spouse chooses a different right option. However, it is unclear under whose custody the daughter should be placed. This film does not take sides and does not ask us to identify with either party. The audience – just like their daughter – must decide for themselves who they believe made the better choice, and whose side they are going to take.Come to the screening of A Separation to witness one of the best illustrations of the weight of making the right choice in the morally and emotionally ambiguous world of ordinary people.No registration required. Please show up 15 minutes before the screening for check-in.

title: The Loyola Project (2022) - Documentary Screening at the Griffith Theater with BSA!
details: Join us and the Black Student Alliance for The Loyola Project (2022)! There will be a 30-minute conversation about the film afterwards.No registration required - we take walk-ins! Please show up 15 minutes before the film starts.In 1963, at the height of the civil rights movement, the Loyola Ramblers of Chicago broke racial barriers and changed college basketball forever.Now, nearly 60 years later, this legendary team is reexamined by Loyola basketball player and co-captain, Lucas Williamson. Woven together with archival footage and modern day interviews, this captivating story continues to provide inspiration in the fight for equality.

title: King Richard - Movie Screening at the Griffith Theater!
details: Join Freewater Presentations this weekend for King Richard(2021), following Richard, Venus, and Serena Williams on their journey to tennis excellence.No registration required - we take walk-ins! Please show up 15 minutes before the film starts.Armed with a clear vision and a brazen 78-page plan, Richard Williams is determined to write his daughters, Venus and Serena, into history. Training on Compton, California's neglected tennis courts--rain or shine--the girls are shaped by their father's unyielding commitment and their mother's balanced perspective and keen intuition, defying the seemingly insurmountable odds and prevailing expectations laid before them. Based on the true story that will inspire the world, "King Richard" follows the uplifting journey of a family whose unwavering resolve and unconditional belief ultimately delivers two of the world's greatest sports legends.

Join a free non-credit-bearing course designed for students at various universities to practice mindfulness, laughter, and comedy and share it with their communities. 100% virtual, you will learn tips and tricks that can boost your overall wellbeing.This group is open to undergraduate and graduate students.*Must be able to commit to Wednesday evening offerings and final performance on March 23rd.Class Dates: February 16th, 23rd, March 2nd, and 16th. Final Performance on March 23rd

title: Lantern Festival Celebration
details: Lantern Festival is a Chinese traditional festival celebrated on the full moon, the fifteenth day of the first month in the lunar Chinese calendar. Usually falling in February, it marks the final day of the traditional Chinese New Year celebrations. The celebration is planned to be hosted on Feb.15th in the afternoon at 4:30pm, at Hudson Quad.

title: GPSG Community Pantry Services
details: Open to patrons on Thursdays 5pm-7pm and Saturdays 12-2PM. The GPSG Community Pantry provides food, clothing, household and personal hygiene items to Graduate and Professional students at Duke University. The pantry offers a weekly grocery bag program and prepared meal program with contactless pickup. Volunteers come to the GPSG House on Wednesdays after 4PM (grocery store order pickup/drop off), Thursdays 3-7PM (bag packing), and Saturdays 12-2PM (bag distribution). The University's COVID-19 guidelines are enforced (e.g., no more than one person/family in the pantry shopping room at a time; social distancing; hand/surface sanitizing). Periodically throughout the week, members of the pantry's Executive Board Team will access the house as necessary to prepare for our services.

title: Luca - Movie Screening at the Griffith Theater!
details: Join us for the charming bildungsroman Luca(2021)!No registration required - we take walk-ins! Please show up 15 minutes before the film starts.Set in a beautiful seaside town on the Italian Riviera, Disney and Pixar's original feature film "Luca" is a coming-of-age story about one young boy experiencing an unforgettable summer filled with gelato, pasta and endless scooter rides. Luca shares these adventures with his newfound best friend, Alberto, but all the fun is threatened by a deeply-held secret: they are sea monsters from another world just below the water's surface.

title: Winter Nature Hike
details: Hey guys! This Sunday at 11am we're gonna host a Winter nature hike at Sandy Creek Park in Southeast Durham. Sandy Creek is a really cool spot- a former wastewater treatment plant that has been turned into a beautiful remediated wetland and forest. This will be a pretty relaxed event and we can focus on whatever people are interested in, including bird identification, trees, etc. A quick way to de-stress before diving into Sunday homework!

title: Dune - Movie Screening at the Griffith Theater!
details: Join us for the American epic sci-fi film, Dune(2021)!No registration required - we take walk-ins! Please show up 15 minutes before the film starts.Paul Atreides, a brilliant and gifted young man born into a great destiny beyond his understanding, must travel to the most dangerous planet in the universe to ensure the future of his family and his people. As malevolent forces explode into conflict over the planet's exclusive supply of the most precious resource in existence, only those who can conquer their own fear will survive.

title: Tea Time with GROW
details: Join the Green Roof and Orchard Workforce (GROW) club for Tea Time on Friday February 4 from 12-1pm. We will serve a variety of locally grown herbal tea blends and talk about our plans for the garden space in 2022. We will discuss garden planning techniques, mapping, and scheduling to make the most of the growing season. Join us to share what you'd like to see from GROW this year, or just enjoy a break from school-work with a hot cup of tea!Please bring your own mug and tea strainer if possible (we will have some available for those who don't!). We will provide hot water and a selection of herbal teas to choose from.

title: Old Movie Night - The Big Lebowski and Schindler's List
details: This weekend, Thursday-Saturday, Freewater Presentations is putting on Old Movie Night! We'll be screening the transcendent classics The Big Lebowski (1998) and Schindler's List (1993).No registration required - we take walk-ins! Please show up 15 minutes before the film starts.The Big Lebowski: Ultimate L.A. slacker Jeff "The Dude" Lebowski, mistaken for a millionaire of the same name, seeks restitution for a rug ruined by debt collectors, enlisting his bowling buddies for help while trying to find the millionaire's missing wife.Schindler's List: In German-occupied Poland during World War II, industrialist Oskar Schindler gradually becomes concerned for his Jewish workforce after witnessing their persecution by the Nazis.

title: GSAID Movie Night
details: The Forbidden StringsThey've been making music together for years, despite the disapproval of the people around them. Akbar, Soori, Mohammed, and Hakim are the only young immigrants in Iran who have formed a rock band. All they miss now is an opportunity to play live. The Forbidden Strings shows the musical foursome struggling to get themselves heard, and follows them in the run-up to a historic day.

title: North Carolina Chinese Lantern Festival
details: "The Triangle's most spectacular holiday tradition is back! Cary's Koka Booth Amphitheatre will once again serve as the home of the North Carolina Chinese Lantern Festival when it returns this winter for an 7th year.The renderings have been approved and Chinese artisans are busy crafting more than 40 all new displays, each one comprised of hundreds of parts, and thousands of LED lights. These larger-than-life lanterns will captivate visitors with their amazing craftsmanship and artistic beauty. Cultural arts performances will take place each night on the main stage."Coming off the heels of record-breaking visitation last year topping 200,000, we know how ready and excited our community is to welcome the North Carolina Chinese Lantern Festival back to Koka Booth Amphitheatre," said William Lewis, Town of Cary Cultural Arts Manager. ""We take seriously our commitment to awe and delight visitors year after year; so, we have some extra special lanterns and performances planned for 2022. North Carolina's 'must see' event will not disappoint.""

title: ASA ROOTing for You
details: The ASA Bean and Sprout program is a great opportunity for freshmen (beans) to get involved with the ASA community and to bond with upperclassmen (sprouts)! This year, our pairing system will match 1-2 beans with a sprout, and you'll have the chance to foster a relationship with them during the year and beyond. Pairings can form a garden with other bean and sprout pairs. Throughout the year, we will hold events where gardens compete to accrue as many seeds (points) to "plant" in their garden. How does a garden accrue seeds? For example, gardens can accrue seed by winning a board game match against another garden. The garden that manages to accrue the most seeds at the end of the year will receive a special prize.Everyone who applies will be able to rank their most preferred beans/sprouts. We will be hosting our first mingling event, ROOTing for You, on October  15th, from 12-2:PM! This is an introductory event for prospective bean and sprouts to meet each other--just bring yourself, and we'll provide the snacks and beverages! Following this event, we will have smaller events for y'all to get to know each other, but sprouts are also highly encouraged to host their own kickbacks. Logistics for these will be released soon, so be on the lookout!

title: Jewish Life at Duke Senior Donor Event: Lox & Lemurs
details: Seniors, never got a chance to see the lemurs during your time at Duke? Now's your chance! Class of 2023 senior donors to Jewish Life at Duke are invited to celebrate their senior year with Lox and Lemurs! Join us for a full-spread bagel brunch on the Freeman Center Patio and then head to our exclusive guided walking tour at the Duke Lemur Center. Interested? Participate in the Senior Giving Challenge by making a senior gift to Jewish Life at Duke at www.tinyurl.com/JLDSenior or via Venmo (search @dukeseniorfund and in the comment box type your netID and "Jewish Life at Duke," and then send a screenshot to jewishlife@duke.edu), and check your inbox for your invitation!Note: Lemur Center Tour spots are limited, so RSVPs for the tour will close when capacity is reached; all senior donors are welcome at the bagel brunch (no capacity limit).Questions? Contact jewishlife@duke.edu

title: Blooms: ASA Picnic
details: Join us for Outreach Team's end-of-the-year picnic at Abele Quad on April 23rd from 12:00-2:00 P.M. Blooms continues our focus on communal growth and the continual process of (re)understanding and (re)imagining what it means to be Asian/American at Duke. Throughout the year, our programming such as Bean & Sprout, All About That BASE, and other events have focused on providing spaces for folks to create pockets of community, (re)build friendships, and meet new friends. We hope that Blooms serves as not only an end-of-the-year event to cap off our time together but also orients us toward the future—a continual commitment to the journey of creating community together now and beyond our time in this space. This event includes food from Pho Express and Lime & Lemon and drinks (water and juice).

title: Den of Wolves Megagame
details: Imagine a game that combines elements of strategy, diplomacy, role-playing, and teamwork, with a massive player count and a complex, dynamic world. That's what a megagame is all about. Whether you're a seasoned player or a newcomer, megagames offer an immersive and unforgettable experience.Den of Wolves is a sci-fi megagame where you will play as a small fleet of interstellar vessels trying to balance survival, politics, and military challenges as you attempt to stay one step ahead of your pursuers, the now infamous Wolves.The game will take place from 12pm - 7pm on April 22nd in the Student Wellness Center. If you are interested in playing please fill out thisso that we can reserve your spot and match you with a role you will enjoy playing. Also, feel free to send theto anyone else you think might be interested! There is a section that will allow you to specify that you would like to be on a team with friends at the end of the form.Please complete theby no later than end of day April 19th, to help us have enough time to properly assign player roles, or we may not be able to take your preferences into account.If you have any questions, don't hesitate to get in touch: csh59@duke.edu

title: Bricks to Stone
details: The Bricks to Stone tradition is back and better than ever!This campus-wide celebration will mark the transition of the first-year class moving from the bricks of East Campus to the gothic stones of West Campus. This tradition has something for everyone (including free food and merch!).First-year students: 3-6 p.m.Start with the block party at Karsh Alumni Center, 3:00 p.m.-4:00 p.m. for music, dessert novelties, games, and Quad graduation cords. Buses will leave East beginning at 2:45 p.m. Frist-year students should get off the bus at the Admissions bus stop. Make sure you arrive to Karsh no later than 4:00 p.m. to join the procession with your Quad up Campus Drive to the Chapel.* President Vincent Price, Dean of Trinity College of Arts and Sciences Gary Bennett, and Dean of Pratt School of Engineering Jerry Lynch, will greet you and formally welcome you to West. They will provide brief remarks and conduct a Class of 2026 pinning ceremony. Afterwards, join your upperclass peers in your West Quad for a party unique to its culture and traditions. Parties will include free food and Quad merch.Upperclass students: 5-6 p.m.Join your classmates for a party in your Quad, 5-6 p.m. Each Quad will host an event unique to their culture. Network with Alumni from your Quad who are back for Reunions weekend. Free food and merch!*Accessibility accommodations upon request.

details: All current undergraduate and graduate students can play!Please sign up here for the tournament between Duke students on April 8th, 1-5pm.RSVP on DukeGroups and fill out this form: https://forms.gle/MHRoMNfZQHL9Xrw27This tournament is hosted by Duke Club Pickleball.Join our GroupMe to stay up-to-date and join the community: https://groupme.com/join_group/85058587/mRClDbs1There will be 2 pools divided by skill-level.1. beginner/low intermediate: USAP self-ratings of approx 1.0 - 3.02. high intermediate/advanced: USAP self-ratings of 3.5 - 5.0(More information on ratings can be found at https://usapickleball.org/tournaments/tournament-player-ratings/player-skill-rating-definitions/)Each bracket will have 12 doubles teams (you can sign up as a pair or as an individual); 48 participant cap total. title: WomC Awards
details: Get excited for the 2022-2023 WomC Awards! The WomC Awards, or Duke Women's Center Awards, are our way of celebrating Duke students who have gone above and beyond in advancing gender equity on our campus. At this event, we celebrate a year's long fellowship with our allies and advocates in social change with awesome speakers, free food, and lots of fun! The WomC Award ceremony recognizes individuals and campus organizations making an impact at Duke and beyond with 5 award categories to honor the amazing contributions of women and femme-identified folks on campus, locally, state-wide, and nationally. To learn more about the award categories or to nominate someone for an award, visit https://bit.ly/23WomCNoms. To register to attend, visit https://bit.ly/Register23WC.

title: "We are here, and we are here to stay" Perkins Exhibit Reveal
details: "We are here, and we are here to stay", is an exhibit that features the narratives and images submitted by the Duke and the local community whose lives have been touched in some way by immigration status. As part of our programming for Undocumented Awareness Week, this exhibit ultimately aims to highlight the voices of often marginalized communities to demonstrate that immigration is not just a topic of national discourse, but something that hits very close to home for our own peers. As such, we invite everyone to visit this exhibit, found on the 1st floor of Perkins Library, throughout the month of March to appreciate the stories of our community.Food Provided

title: Student-Only Exhibition Opening | Spirit in the Land
details: Join MUSE at the Nasher Museum of Art for a student-only celebration of the new exhibition,.Featuring student DJs, Ben Rubin and Helen Jennings.Enjoy free food and beverages from the Nasher Café.The event is free and open to all Duke students.Spirit in the Landis a contemporary art exhibition that examines today’s urgent ecological concerns from a cultural perspective, demonstrating how intricately our identities and natural environments are intertwined. Through their artwork, thirty artists show us how rooted in the earth our most cherished cultural traditions are, how our relationship to land and water shapes us as individuals and communities. The works reflect the restorative potential of our connection to nature and exemplify how essential both biodiversity and cultural diversity are to our survival.Food Provided (Free food and beverage from the Nasher Cafe. )
location: Nasher Museum of Art at Duke University

title: Converge Afterparty 2023
details: Converge is an annual performing arts showcase hosted by Duke Asian Students Association. Duke's Asian communities are vast and multifaceted, but we are also segmented. As a whole, we have a hard time actually coming together to share our various cultures, experiences, and art around a central theme. Duke ASA hopes to hold a space every spring for Duke's Asian communities to converge, to celebrate what our identities and experiences mean to us as Asian/Americans. Converge Afterparty continues to celebrate our showcase and our segmented identities.

title: Earthquake Fundraising Run
details: Join the Duke community in a 7.8 km run on East Campus to help fundraise money for earthquake relief in Turkey.  The 7.8 km run is to signify the 7.8 magnitude of one of the earthquakes that devasted the region.  The program is being coordinated by Stanley Borden, a member of the men's basketball team, and members of the Turkish and Syrian communities.The run will start at Baldwin Auditorium at 3:00 and there will be a celebration for runners and the Duke Community at 5:00 to announce the amount of money raised.Donate here: https://tickets.duke.edu/students/Online/default.asp?BOparam::WScontent::loadArticle::permalink=earthquake&BOparam::WScontent::loadArticle::context_id=Know members from outside of Duke who want to join? title: The Human Spotify | Acoustic Karaoke
details: JOHN RUSH is "The Human Spotify", because he has over 85 hours of music in his head!! You could see 42 2-hour shows and never hear a song twice!! He has 2 GIANT request books. Anything from current songs to favorite songs you grew up with!! Students pick songs they want to hear and write them on little post-it notes, then stick them all over the stage. This lets the audience get involved and also makes sure he plays songs they want to hear!!ACOUSTIC KARAOKE is fast becoming the must-have event on campus!! Students get to sing and have a great time!! Are you a confident singer? Or are you little shy? Either way it's ok because John is performing the song while you sing with him. It's like Live Band Karaoke, but better!! It's tons of fun and really gets the students involved because it lets them become the show!!

title: Indoor Cycling Class at Sweat Lab
details: Have a New Year's Resolution you're getting started on? Me too. Maybe this private cycling class at the Sweat Lab in Durham will help get things going! The class includes mimosas afterwards, a place to fill your water bottles, towels, and clip in cycling shoes. If you already own a pair, you are welcome to bring them. (Their bikes pedals are compatible with SPD and Delta clips.)"THE SWEAT LAB delivers sweaty, challenging and innovative classes for all levels. From indoor cycling to toning, including barre, yoga and sculpt. Our passionate instructors offer uniquely planned, beat driven classes paired with curated playlists designed to motivate and inspire.This is your space to let go, achieve your goals, and engage. Unleash your physical and mental strengths – see results in the studio and out in your world. After all, who's more amazing than you? No one."

title: STEMixer
details: Having trouble connecting with your fellow STEM students? Feeling lost navigating this primarily male-dominated field? Join the Women's Center for our STEMixer and chat with professors and faculty in your STEM field and learn about their strategies for success. Learn about advancing gender equity in the field and paving your own path to career and personal success. Some questions to ask your professors (and potential future colleagues!): What takes you out of your comfort zone? How can I make the most of my college experience? What's it like being a woman in your field? What do would equity look like in your field? Register at https://bit.ly/STEMixer23 or use the DukeGroups link!Food Provided

title: Meshroom
details: Meshroom is a performance environment that forms an intellectual/intentional community around an open dancefloor. It is a space for transcending narrow languages, ungrounding from fixed realities, and co-creating temporary worlds in movement. Meshroom is shaped by the movement, dreams, hopes and queerness of everyone in the room: it is a weaving of wild minds and soft bodies. All visitors are welcome to move, rest, witness, think, melt and dance with live music and occasional performances.This event is free and open to all. Drop-in and drop-out. Bring a friend.

details: The Dongzhi Festival or Winter Solstice Festival is a traditional Chinese festival celebrated during the Dongzhi solar term. To celebrate this traditional Chinese holiday, Duke Chinese Dance will rent out a space for its members and the general public to hang out, listen to music, make food and reflect on the experiences of being Chinese-American or of Chinese descent in the U.S. We will kick off the day with a boba photoshoot in the Duke Garden from 11:30am to 1:30pm. Meet us at the Koi pond and come with your fall-themed outfits! At night we will have our festival in Blue Light starting at 8pm and ending at 11pm where there will be drinks and snacks for everyone.Food Provided (Boba)

title: Women+ Climb Night
details: Women+ Outdoor Adventures is a gender-expansive community created to empower women, intersex, and genderfluid individuals to explore rock climbing, the gym, and outdoor spaces together.Our climb nights led by trained Outdoor Adventures staff members will center on different themes like technique building or endurance. The focus of this program is individual skill development within an inclusive, supportive community, and all levels of climbing ability are welcome.Space is limited. Pre-registration is required on MyRec.

title: GlobeMed Community Building Event
details: GlobeMed is a global health club, focused on raising awareness for current global health issues. We have weekly meetings to discuss such issues and collaborate to initiate action to potentially provide aid, such as our monthly campaigns.To promote engagement and community building, we are hosting an event to eat hot pot at Szechuan Mansion with the first 15 individuals who sign up. Given that GlobeMed does not have selective membership, this event is open to any student who may have an interest in Global Health or in joining GlobeMed. We believe that such bonding experiences will help us develop a stronger, more dedicated community invested in promoting rightful actions towards global health issues.

title: DARIN AND BROOKE ALDRIDGE
details: Unique vocal talent, accomplished songwriting and commanding instrumental skills are just a few of Darin and Brooke Aldridge's gifts. Brooke is a four-time consecutive winner for Female Vocalist of the Year for the International Bluegrass Music Association and together with their band, they were nominated for 2021 Vocal Group of the Year.Their latest album, This Life We're Livin,' is a warm, cohesive collection that takes you on a journey into the lives and story of Darin and Brooke. It features original standouts, including "Grand Ole Circle," "Livin' Mama's Dream," and "My Life's Living Me," which offer a clear-eyed commentary on the joys and challenges of their musical success.We are proud to welcome this North Carolina-based duo to Durham for an evening of unforgettable bluegrass at American Tobacco Campus.
